<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-payroll-tax-error-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;Payroll tax calculating wrong,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="qb-help-payroll-tax-error-in-brief-text">When people say QuickBooks is calculating payroll taxes wrong, they usually mean one of a few things: the federal or state <em>withholding</em> on a paycheck looks too high or too low; the state unemployment (SUI) amount doesn&rsquo;t match the rate the agency assigned you; a <em>local</em> or jurisdiction tax isn&rsquo;t being withheld at all; or the <em>payroll liabilities</em> report doesn&rsquo;t tie to what was actually withheld from employees and paid to the agencies. The numbers are downstream of two things &mdash; the tax table QuickBooks is using, and how each employee, company, and agency is set up.</p>
      <p>The good news is most of these trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; updating the tax table and correcting the setup clears a large share of cases. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> change is the rate or rule itself: those are set by the IRS and your state and local agencies, and we apply them, we don&rsquo;t decide them. And the steps don&rsquo;t <em>file</em> anything &mdash; filing your payroll returns and handling any notice or penalty is your CPA or EA&rsquo;s work (or Intuit&rsquo;s payroll e-file service, if you run Intuit payroll). What we do is make the books and the setup correct, and reconcile the liabilities so the filing is built on numbers that tie.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

